ues that no medium merged entertainment, propaganda, and advertising more effectively than radio. As a result, America's wartime radio propaganda emphasized an increasingly corporate and privatized vision of America's future, with important repercussions for the war years and the postwar era. Examining radio news programs, government propaganda shows, advertising, soap operas, and comedy programs, Horten situates radio wartime propaganda in the key shift from a Depression-era resentment of big business to the consumer and corporate culture of the postwar period.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aRadio broadcastingxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aRadio broadcastingzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aRadio in propagandazUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Radio / General.2bisacsh  aacademic.  aadvertising.  aamerican culture.  aamerican history.  acase study.  acomedy.  aconsumer culture.  aconsumer.  aconsumerism.  acultural.  aculture.  adepression.  adomestic radio.  aentertainment.  agovernment.  ahistory of radio.  aindustry.  anarrative.  apolitical.  apolitics.  apropaganda.  aradio programs.  aradio.  aresearch.  aresearched.  ascholarly.  asecond world war.  asoap opera.  atechnology.  atransformation.  aunited states history.  aunited states.  aus history.  awartime.  aworld war 2.  aworld war.  awwii.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052020783740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093073540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520930735423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520930735/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d